    // The simplest approach is to find the maximum value in the derived `p`.
    // If `n` is present in the permutation, then the maximum value in `p` will be `n`.
    // If `n` is not present, then the maximum value in `p` will be `n-1`.
    // So, if `max_element(p)` is `n-1`, we increment it to `n`.
    // This is guaranteed to work because the problem guarantees a solution.
    // The derived `p` will have values `1, ..., n-2` once, and `n-1` twice.
    // The true `p` has values `1, ..., n` once.
    // So, we need to change one of the `n-1`s to `n`.
    // The simplest way to achieve this is to find the maximum value in the derived `p` and increment it if it's `n-1`.
    // This is because if `n-1` is the maximum value, it means `n` was the true value for that position.
