        // This is equivalent to checking if (abs_n - k) % 2 == 0.
        // Because abs_n and abs_m have same parity, abs_n - abs_m is even.
        // So (abs_n + abs_m) % 2 == (abs_n - abs_m + 2*abs_m) % 2 == (abs_n - abs_m) % 2.
        // This means (abs_n + abs_m) % 2 == 0.
        // So if (abs_n - k) % 2 == 0, then k has the same parity as abs_n.
        // If abs_n and abs_m have same parity, then abs_n has same parity as abs_m.
        // So k has same parity as abs_n and abs_m.
        // This means k and (abs_n + abs_m) have the same parity.
        // This is the condition for being able to reach (abs_n, abs_m) in k moves.
        // If (abs_n - k) % 2 == 0, then k and abs_n have the same parity.
        // Since abs_n and abs_m have the same parity, k, abs_n, and abs_m all have the same parity.
        // This means (abs_n + abs_m) and k have the same parity.
        // In this case, all remaining_moves can be converted into diagonal moves.
