#include <algorithm>
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>

int main() {
    std::ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    std::cin.tie(NULL);
    int t;
    std::cin >> t;
    while (t--) {
        int n;
        std::cin >> n;
        std::vector<long long> a(2 * n);
        for (int i = 0; i < 2 * n; ++i) {
            std::cin >> a[i];
        }
        std::sort(a.begin(), a.end());
        // The problem asks to partition 2n students into two classes,
        // each with an odd number of students.
        // Let the sizes of the two classes be S1 and S2.
        // S1 + S2 = 2n.
        // S1 must be odd, S2 must be odd.
        // If S1 is odd, then S2 = 2n - S1. Since 2n is even and S1 is odd, S2 must be odd.
        // So, we just need to ensure S1 is odd.
        // The smallest possible odd size is 1.
        // The largest possible odd size is 2n-1.
        //
        // Consider the sorted array a_1, a_2, ..., a_{2n}.
        //
        // Let the first class have size S1 = 2k+1. Its median will be the (k+1)-th element.
        // Let the second class have size S2 = 2n - (2k+1). Its median will be the (n-k)-th element.
        //
        // To minimize the absolute difference between medians, we want the medians to be as close as possible.
        //
        // Consider the specific partition where the first class takes the first n elements
        // and the second class takes the remaining n elements.
        // This is not allowed because n might be even.
        //
        // However, if we sort the entire array, the median of any odd-sized subset
        // will be one of the elements in the sorted array.
        //
        // Let's consider the specific case where the first class consists of elements
        // a_1, ..., a_n and the second class consists of a_{n+1}, ..., a_{2n}.
        // This is not a valid partition because n might be even.
        //
        // The key insight for this problem is that to minimize the difference between medians,
        // we should try to make the medians as close as possible.
        //
        // If we sort the entire array `a`, the elements are `a[0], a[1], ..., a[2n-1]`.
        //
        // Consider the partition where one class takes `n` elements from the lower half
        // and the other class takes `n` elements from the upper half.
        // This is not quite right because class sizes must be odd.
        //
        // The crucial observation is that if we sort the entire array `a`,
        // the median of the first class will be `a[i]` for some `i`,
        // and the median of the second class will be `a[j]` for some `j`.
        //
        // To minimize `|median1 - median2|`, we want to pick `a[i]` and `a[j]` that are close.
        //
        // Let's consider the elements `a[n-1]` and `a[n]`.
        // `a[n-1]` is the largest of the first `n` elements.
        // `a[n]` is the smallest of the last `n` elements.
        //
        // If we form one class using elements `a[0], ..., a[n-1]` and another using `a[n], ..., a[2n-1]`,
        // this is not valid if `n` is even.
        //
        // However, if we consider the elements `a[n-1]` and `a[n]`,
        // `a[n-1]` is the median of the first `n` elements if `n` is odd.
        // `a[n]` is the median of the last `n` elements if `n` is odd.
        //
        // The problem states that each class must have an odd number of students.
        // Let the first class have $S_1$ students and the second class have $S_2$ students.
        // $S_1 = 2k_1 + 1$ and $S_2 = 2k_2 + 1$.
        // $S_1 + S_2 = 2n$.
        //
        // If we sort the entire array $a_0, a_1, \dots, a_{2n-1}$.
        //
        // Consider the partition where the first class consists of $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$ and the second class consists of $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$.
        // This is not a valid partition because $n$ can be even.
        //
        // The key insight is that the minimum difference will always be achieved by taking `a[n-1]` and `a[n]` as the medians.
        //
        // Let's prove this.
        // Suppose we have two classes, $C_1$ and $C_2$, with sizes $S_1 = 2k_1+1$ and $S_2 = 2k_2+1$.
        // Let $m_1$ be the median of $C_1$ and $m_2$ be the median of $C_2$.
        //
        // After sorting the entire array $a_0, \dots, a_{2n-1}$:
        //
        // The median of $C_1$ must be some $a_i$.
        // The median of $C_2$ must be some $a_j$.
        //
        // To minimize $|a_i - a_j|$, we want $i$ and $j$ to be adjacent or as close as possible.
        //
        // Consider the element $a_{n-1}$. It is the $(n)$-th element in the sorted array.
        // Consider the element $a_n$. It is the $(n+1)$-th element in the sorted array.
        //
        // We can always construct a partition such that $a_{n-1}$ is the median of one class and $a_n$ is the median of the other.
        //
        // For example, let $C_1 = \{a_0, a_1, \dots, a_{n-1}\}$ and $C_2 = \{a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}\}$.
        // This is not valid if $n$ is even.
        //
        // However, we can always form a class of size $n$ (if $n$ is odd) or $n-1$ (if $n$ is even)
        // around $a_{n-1}$ and another class of size $n$ (if $n$ is odd) or $n+1$ (if $n$ is even) around $a_n$.
        //
        // The problem is simpler than it seems.
        // The minimum difference is always `a[n] - a[n-1]`.
        //
        // Why?
        // Consider the sorted array $a_0, a_1, \dots, a_{2n-1}$.
        // We need to pick $S_1$ elements for class 1 and $S_2$ elements for class 2, where $S_1, S_2$ are odd.
        //
        // Let $m_1$ be the median of class 1 and $m_2$ be the median of class 2.
        //
        // Suppose $m_1 < m_2$.
        // For $m_1$ to be the median of its class, there must be at least $(S_1-1)/2$ elements less than or equal to $m_1$ in its class, and at least $(S_1-1)/2$ elements greater than or equal to $m_1$ in its class.
